		<header>
			
			<h1>Trade negotiations process in Pacific up in the air</h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 April 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>At the EPA negotiations preparatory meeting in Apia, Samoa, at the beginning of February 2011, Secretary-General Tuiloma Neroni Slade of the Pacific Island Forum highlighted the extent of issues outstanding in the EPA negotiations, including contentious issues, some of them region-specific and some common across the ACP. He maintained that these needed to be resolved if the negotiations were to move forward. He maintained that the process of negotiations had intensified in 2010, with ‘substantial work on market access offers’ having been undertaken. Progress had also been made on the fisheries chapter and customs text. Secretary-General Slade argued that any final agreement ‘must go beyond market access and have a strong development focus’.</p><p>However, according to press reports a cloud hung over the February meeting, in the form of a paper tabled by Papua New Guinea calling for responsibility for trade negotiations to be shifted from the Pacific Island Forum Secretariat to the Office of the Chief Trade Advisor (OCTA), a proposal reported to be the result of ‘a breakdown of trust between the Pacific and the Forum Secretariat’. Press analysis notes that such a reform would ‘allow Fiji to return to the negotiating table’, since while Fiji has been suspended as a Pacific Forum member it remains a member of the body to which the OCTA reports.</p><p>The EC, meanwhile, has reiterated its commitment to concluding a comprehensive EPA with the Pacific region, including all the countries of the region. However the EC acknowledges the diverse realities of Pacific island countries, and is therefore ‘ready to look at other formats as well’.</p><p>Looking beyond the EPA negotiations, Fiji is exploring possibilities for renewing sugar exports to Japan, with the Sojitz Corporation sending a team to Fiji to discuss a possible shipment. Fiji is also exploring the possibility of exporting sugar to Australia, given the devastation wrought in Queensland by recent floods and cyclones. This forms part of wider aspirations to shift Fijian sugar production up the value chain towards the packaged white-sugar market. An evaluation of the technical and economic feasibility of such a development is shortly to be launched. At the same time, Fiji Sugar Corporation’s Executive Chairman Abdul Khan has stressed that the company will ‘first try and fulfil our contractual requirements to Tate and Lyle’ (some 200,000 tonnes a year) before seeking to supply markets elsewhere.</p>
		
		
