				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Some of the most contentious issues around the concluded IEPA relate to the rules of origin for fisheries products, which require only single-stage processing to gain originating status. The European Parliament has called on the EC to suspend the revised rules if their application threatens ‘a disruptive impact’ on the European industry. Such a suspension would be in contradiction to PNG’s reasons for signing an interim EPA as, apart from Fiji’s interest in sugar exports, it represents one of the principal motivations for the Pacific region to conclude an EPA with the EU. Such a move would potentially set a dangerous precedent for the application of preferential trade concessions, since it subordinates preferences to their impact on EU industries, thereby creating uncertainty for investors.</p><p>More broadly, Pacific ACP (PACP) governments see simplified and workable rules of origin as a means of stimulating greater value-added processing in food product chains and facilitating a movement away from dependence on primary exports. This is seen as critical in an era of heightened commodity-price volatility and increasingly dynamic global markets. This is part of a wider policy focus on supporting movement up the value chain in the Pacific.</p><p>A September 2010 paper from the Secretariat of the Pacific Community (SPC) concluded that the lack of competitiveness of PACP products is the result of problems spanning the entire supply chain. The paper identified the approach that should be taken, including meeting the technical requirements for market access, SPS standards, and understanding the changing consumer preferences in target export markets.</p><p>This approach in the region can be seen behind FSC’s aspirations to move up the sugar value chain and develop new export markets. The current high world market prices and shifting patterns of global sugar demand would appear to offer real opportunities in this regard. However, this begs the question of how this transition is to be financed and managed, given the financial difficulties faced by FSC. These financial and personnel constraints can be seen as symptomatic of wider challenges facing the Pacific food and agricultural sector.</p>
		</div>
		
